To prevent Command Injection vulnerabilities in Java code, you should not directly pass user input to the `Runtime.exec()` method. Instead, you should validate and sanitize user input before executing any external commands. One common approach is to use `ProcessBuilder` class, which allows you to set the command and arguments separately.

Here is the updated secure version of your code using `ProcessBuilder`:

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.InputStreamReader;

public class SecureCommandExecutionExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));

        System.out.print("Enter a command to execute: ");
        String command = reader.readLine();

        // Split the command into separate arguments
        String[] commandArgs = command.split("\\s+");

        // Build the process with sanitized input
        ProcessBuilder pb = new ProcessBuilder(commandArgs);

        // Start the process
        Process process = pb.start();

        // Read and print output
        BufferedReader outputReader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(process.getInputStream()));
        String line;
        while ((line = outputReader.readLine()) != null) {
            System.out.println(line);
        }
    }
}
``

